phic fieldwork with trans people obtaining gender reassignment surgery in Thailand, Aizura maps the uneven use of medical protocols to show how national and regional health care systems and labor economies contribute to and limit transnational mobility. Aizura positions transgender travel as a form of biomedical tourism, examining how understandings of race, gender, and aesthetics shape global cosmetic surgery cultures and how economic and racially stratified marketing and care work create the ideal transgender subject as an implicitly white, global citizen. In so doing, he shows how understandings of travel and mobility depend on the historical architectures of colonialism and contemporary patterns of global consumption and labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aMedical tourism. 0aSex change. 0aTransgender peoplexTravel. 4aLAMMY finalist. 4aLambda Literary Awards. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002642zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002642.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles